**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<div newNamespace>  
<setup>
  <math name="a">8</math>
  <math name="b">5</math>
  <math name="c">1</math>
  <math name="d">6</math>
  <math name="e">4</math>
  <math name="f">1</math>
  <math name="g">2</math>
  <math name="line1x2" simplify>$a + $c</math>
  <math name="line1y2" simplify>$b + $d</math>
</setup>
<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p>

<example>
<p><em>Find the value of <m>k</m> so that the two lines are perpendicular.</em></p>
<p><em>Line 1 contains the points <m>($a, $b)</m> and <m>($line1x2, $line1y2)</m>. </em></p>
<p><em>Line 2 contains the points <m>(3, 9)</m> and <m>(15, k)</m>.</em></p>

<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<ul>
  <li><p>When two lines are perpendicular, their slopes are opposite in sign and reciprocal values. We first  compute the slope given the two points indicated for Line 1.</p></li>
  <li><p><m>m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} = <math name="m1">($line1y2 - $b)/($line1x2 - $a)</math> = $m1{simplify}</m></p>
  </li>
  <li>The slope for Line 1 tells us that the slope for its perpendicular, Line 2, is <math name="mPerp">-1/6</math>. Therefore, we can substitute this value in the slope formula for Line 2, and solve for <m>k</m>
    <md>
      <mrow>$mPerp &= <math>(k - 9)/(15 - 3)</math></mrow>
      <mrow><math>$mPerp (12)</math> &= k - 9</mrow>
      <mrow>7 &= k</mrow>
    </md>
  </li>
  <li><p>We can graph our solution to check our answer:</p>
    <graph xmin="-1" xmax="19" ymin="-1" ymax="19">
      <line name="line1" through="$P1 $P2">
        <label>Line 1</label>
      </line>
      <point name="P1" fixed coords="($a, $b)">
        <label>$P1.coords</label>
      </point>
      <point name="P2" fixed coords="($line1x2, $line1y2)">
        <label>$P2.coords</label>
      </point>
      <line name="line2" through="$P3 $P4" styleNumber="2">
        <label>Line 2</label>
      </line>
      <point name="P3" fixed coords="(15,7)" styleNumber="2">
        <label>$P3.coords</label>
      </point>
      <point name="P4" fixed coords="(3,9)" styleNumber="2">
        <label>$P4.coords</label>
      </point>
    </graph>
  </li>
</ul>


</example>
</div>

  </hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p><m>k = $sol</m></p>

</solution>
</problem>




